Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue (adjusted for inflation)

Question(s) for Analysis¶

1) Which genres are most popular from year to year?
2) What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

Obsevations from the dataset¶

1) There are missing values in columns (imdb_id, cast, homepage, director, tagline, keywords, overview, generes, production_campanies)
2) There is a row that is duplicated.
3) Some movies in the database have zero budget or zero revenue or zero runtime, that is there value has not been recorded
4) more than 50% of the values of budget and renenue columns have values less than 10
5) more than 80% of the values of popularity column have values less than 1
6) 75% of the values of vote couts column have values less than or equal to 145
7) vote_count is different for all the movies from 10 to 9767, so we cannot directly conculed the popularity of the movies based on the average vote count but we can make weighted votes based on vote count and vote average

1) Remove some columns with missing values and the columns we wont use.
2) Remove duplicated rows.
3) Remove rows with values less than 30 in budget and the revenue columns
4) Remove nan values
5) Get The most popular genere from the whole dataset

Conclusions¶

At this analysis of The Movie Dataset (TMDb) we determine the answers to these two questions. 1) Which genres are most popular from year to year?
2) What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
and many other question but we are focusing on these two main questions.

then we got that The most highly rated movie genre by year varied, but the Animation genre was the genre that had the highest average rating across the most years. This may be because Animations are more suitable for all ages and can have good colors and imaginations.

The most vote average movie genre by year varied as well, but the Documentary genre was the genre that had the highest vote average across the most years. This may be because documentaries are more serious productions that tend to be polished and because less of them are produced.

The most budget movie genre by year varied as well, but the History genre was the genre that had the highest badget across the most years. This may be because history movies materials and location costs too much to locks like old ones.

Finally, a higher average budget does appear to have a very slight association with a higher average revenue.

With this information it can be determined that in order to make a more successful movie measured by revenue, one should make a documentary with the highest budget possible, and that to make a more successful movie, one should make adventure movies with higher budgets when able.
